that nothing you
could possibly write

00:27:04.930 --> 00:27:07.778
would seem stranger
than those stories.

00:27:07.778 --> 00:27:09.236
ELIOT PEPER: It's
very frustrating.

00:27:09.236 --> 00:27:10.640
DAVID ALLISON: Right, right.

00:27:10.640 --> 00:27:16.610
And I'm curious-- you've
written four books now.

00:27:16.610 --> 00:27:19.390
How have you learned
to basically adapt

00:27:19.390 --> 00:27:21.460
or tune the story lines?

00:27:21.460 --> 00:27:23.890
Because they come across to
me, having read all of them,

00:27:23.890 --> 00:27:26.730
they come across to me as
actually quite believable.

00:27:26.730 --> 00:27:28.100
Everything fits together.

00:27:28.100 --> 00:27:32.920
It's vaguely plausible
and you go, OK, I see it.

00:27:32.920 --> 00:27:35.350
Whereas when I read about
Elizabeth Holmes' story

00:27:35.350 --> 00:27:38.590
and I read about Theranos, I
was like, that's impossible.

00:27:38.590 --> 00:27:41.660
I can't possibly believe
that that actually happened.

00:27:41.660 --> 00:27:44.090
And I'm curious
to see basically,

00:27:44.090 --> 00:27:46.975
how have you developed a sort of
mechanism for tuning the story?

00:27:46.975 --> 00:27:48.850
ELIOT PEPER: So basically,
what you're saying

00:27:48.850 --> 00:27:51.294
is I'm not imaginative enough?

00:27:51.294 --> 00:27:52.730
DAVID ALLISON: I like that take.

00:27:52.730 --> 00:27:53.270
That's good.

00:27:53.270 --> 00:27:54.335
Yeah, it's a criticism.

00:27:57.321 --> 00:27:58.820
ELIOT PEPER: I'm
always blown away--

00:27:58.820 --> 00:28:01.740
I think fact is stranger
than fiction always.

00:28:01.740 --> 00:28:03.420
Another one that
really blew me away

00:28:03.420 --> 00:28:07.800
was when the Pamana
Papers scandal came out.

00:28:07.800 --> 00:28:11.680
My first trilogy focuses
on financial crime.

00:28:11.680 --> 00:28:15.030
And so I was like, wow.

00:28:15.030 --> 00:28:15.860
This is way better.

00:28:20.542 --> 00:28:21.750
I'm trying to think about it.

00:28:21.750 --> 00:28:24.690
I don't know that I try to
come up-- the thing that I care

00:28:24.690 --> 00:28:27.130
most about in the
creative process

00:28:27.130 --> 00:28:32.510
is actually not really
the plausibility of either

00:28:32.510 --> 00:28:34.850
any technology that might
be involved in a story

00:28:34.850 --> 00:28:37.380
or even the plot
of a story so much.

00:28:37.380 --> 00:28:41.220
I really think that the
most important piece for me

00:28:41.220 --> 00:28:43.090
as a reader when
I'm reading a book

00:28:43.090 --> 00:28:45.570
is that characters
are consistent.

00:28:45.570 --> 00:28:52.830
Because if you have characters
that you believe act in the way

00:28:52.830 --> 00:28:57.090
that they would, even if
you were in their shoes,

00:28:57.090 --> 00:28:59.300
you might act differently,
but if you really

00:28:59.300 --> 00:29:01.480
believe they're
acting consistently,

00:29:01.480 --> 00:29:04.730
you can almost go
along with anything.

00:29:04.730 --> 00:29:07.200
Because we're in their lives.

00:29:07.200 --> 00:29:11.245
Fiction allows us to get inside
of someone else's life, inside

00:29:11.245 --> 00:29:11.870
of their heart.

00:29:11.870 --> 00:29:19.020
And so if you're with them
and you're on their journey,

00:29:19.020 --> 00:29:21.590
so that's the thing that I
actually pay the most attention

00:29:21.590 --> 00:29:26.420
to in the creative process,
not the larger world issues.

00:29:26.420 --> 00:29:31.270
It's much more personal.

00:29:31.270 --> 00:29:36.680
And often, that can be very
frustrating when I fail at it.

00:29:36.680 --> 00:29:39.550
So if you have a
critical decision that

00:29:39.550 --> 00:29:42.040
doesn't feel consistent,
that can really

00:29:42.040 --> 00:29:44.890
throw off a whole story.

00:29:44.890 --> 00:29:48.071
And so those are the things
that I try to pay attention to

00:29:48.071 --> 00:29:49.070
in the creative process.

00:29:52.302 --> 00:29:55.820
RICK KLAU: You have been
very open in engaging

00:29:55.820 --> 00:30:01.010
the community of readers who've
grown around these books.

00:30:01.010 --> 00:30:02.390
Similar to David's
point, I think

00:30:02.390 --> 00:30:05.780
there are small moments
for me that are really

00:30:05.780 --> 00:30:09.580
the ones that lend the air of
verisimilitude to the story.

00:30:09.580 --> 00:30:13.110
I remember in "Uncommon Stock"
reading about their first term

00:30:13.110 --> 00:30:14.960
sheet negotiation.

00:30:14.960 --> 00:30:17.220
And it's a very minor detail.

00:30:17.220 --> 00:30:20.320
It might have been a couple
of sentences in a paragraph.

00:30:20.320 --> 00:30:23.310
But I'd seen that exact
situation play out

00:30:23.310 --> 00:30:28.920
with inexperienced entrepreneurs
who really got taken for a ride

00:30:28.920 --> 00:30:32.260
from unscrupulous investors
who were exploiting

00:30:32.260 --> 00:30:35.060
the imbalance of power
that existed at the time.

00:30:35.060 --> 00:30:38.940
And hearing you,
almost as a throwaway,

00:30:38.940 --> 00:30:42.180
it made it very easy for
me to live in that world

00:30:42.180 --> 00:30:45.860
and believe that you knew
what you were talking about.

00:30:45.860 --> 00:30:49.240
What other pieces
of feedback have you

00:30:49.240 --> 00:30:53.220
heard from your readers that
surprised you or informed

00:30:53.220 --> 00:30:58.550
future writing that you've done,
or do they become your sources

00:30:58.550 --> 00:30:59.365
for future stories?

00:30:59.365 --> 00:31:02.160
ELIOT PEPER: Absolutely, yes.

00:31:02.160 --> 00:31:06.560
So I totally agree with you,
and to follow up on your point,

00:31:06.560 --> 00:31:08.770
I think that those
little details actually

00:31:08.770 --> 00:31:12.180
do much more for, I guess
you call it worldbuilding

00:31:12.180 --> 00:31:17.780
or for verisimilitude than
the bigger ticket stuff,

00:31:17.780 --> 00:31:20.200
than the big
explosions, or things

00:31:20.200 --> 00:31:23.430
that are obviously descriptive.

00:31:23.430 --> 00:31:27.810
And so knowing that, I
try to really research

00:31:27.810 --> 00:31:31.320
a lot to support those
kinds of details in a story.

00:31:31.320 --> 00:31:34.520
So a good example
is in exit strategy,

00:31:34.520 --> 00:31:37.330
which is the final book
in my first trilogy.

00:31:37.330 --> 00:31:41.530
During that book,
the startup that

00:31:41.530 --> 00:31:45.520
has been active since the
beginning of the trilogy

00:31:45.520 --> 00:31:46.690
goes through an IPO.

00:31:46.690 --> 00:31:50.240
And they're also going
through this climax

00:31:50.240 --> 00:31:52.310
of discovering this
international conspiracy

00:31:52.310 --> 00:31:53.430
at the same time.

00:31:53.430 --> 00:31:55.180
And I've never been
through an IPO.

00:31:55.180 --> 00:31:56.730
I don't know what that's like.

00:31:56.730 --> 00:32:00.810
I've never been through
it in any way or form.

00:32:00.810 --> 00:32:03.620
But I knew that the
protagonist, she's the CEO,

00:32:03.620 --> 00:32:07.300
it has to feel legit.

00:32:07.300 --> 00:32:11.040
I'm certainly not going to
walk through the IPO process,

00:32:11.040 --> 00:32:14.350
because that's going
to be really boring.

00:32:14.350 --> 00:32:17.850
But she has to have a few
experiences or thoughts

00:32:17.850 --> 00:32:19.800
about it that feel right.

00:32:19.800 --> 00:32:27.550
And if you go on Google
and research IPO process,

00:32:27.550 --> 00:32:30.450
it's totally unhelpful,
because you're

00:32:30.450 --> 00:32:33.220
going to find things that
are like white papers written

00:32:33.220 --> 00:32:36.730
by law firms that explain
how the process works.

00:32:36.730 --> 00:32:40.390
That doesn't tell me
anything about what

00:32:40.390 --> 00:32:43.770
would be inside a
founder's head as they are

00:32:43.770 --> 00:32:47.020
going through that experience.

00:32:47.020 --> 00:32:51.930
And so I ended up reaching out
and asking for introductions

00:32:51.930 --> 00:32:56.160
to CEOs who had been through
that process multiple times

00:32:56.160 --> 00:32:57.590
and interviewed them.

00:32:57.590 --> 00:33:00.730
And I actually really
enjoyed the interviews,

00:33:00.730 --> 00:33:03.840
because I would make
a terrible reporter,

00:33:03.840 --> 00:33:06.430
because I don't take notes.

00:33:06.430 --> 00:33:07.850
I don't record anything.

00:33:07.850 --> 00:33:10.679
But for novels, it's
excellent, because I

00:33:10.679 --> 00:33:12.220
would talk to them
for about an hour,

00:33:12.220 --> 00:33:14.420
just ask about what
their experience was.

00:33:14.420 --> 00:33:15.900
And you discover
these funny things

00:33:15.900 --> 00:33:17.950
that when you're on
your road show, which

00:33:17.950 --> 00:33:20.327
is when you're flying
around and pitching all

00:33:20.327 --> 00:33:21.910
of these large
institutional investors

00:33:21.910 --> 00:33:25.472
that would participate in your
IPO, you're always on the run,

00:33:25.472 --> 00:33:26.930
because you're
giving presentations

00:33:26.930 --> 00:33:28.480
after presentation all day long.

00:33:28.480 --> 00:33:31.896
And you always get this
terrible rubber chicken,

00:33:31.896 --> 00:33:34.020
you know, like the kind
when you're at a conference

00:33:34.020 --> 00:33:36.700
and it's totally tasteless.

00:33:36.700 --> 00:33:39.900
So a number of people
mentioned that,

00:33:39.900 --> 00:33:43.440
how it was so-- you had to
eat your rubber chicken as

00:33:43.440 --> 00:33:45.290
quickly as you could.

00:33:45.290 --> 00:33:47.260
So it's those little
things that make

00:33:47.260 --> 00:33:49.250
it work and make it feel right.

00:33:49.250 --> 00:33:55.100
And so I try to do that, and
not just on the business side.

00:33:55.100 --> 00:33:58.230
So like that trilogy deals
with money laundering

00:33:58.230 --> 00:33:59.850
and financial malfeasance.

00:33:59.850 --> 00:34:03.380
So I interviewed
federal investigators,

00:34:03.380 --> 00:34:06.270
money laundering experts at
some of the major international

00:34:06.270 --> 00:34:07.890
banks.

00:34:07.890 --> 00:34:13.609
And the same is true for
"Cumulus," on different aspects

00:34:13.609 --> 00:34:16.150
of the story where I wanted to
make sure I was getting things

00:34:16.150 --> 00:34:16.310
right.

00:34:16.310 --> 00:34:17.760
I mean, it was
very helpful that I

00:34:17.760 --> 00:34:20.179
was writing about where
I lived, because I

00:34:20.179 --> 00:34:22.629
know some of those details.

00:34:22.629 --> 00:34:24.170
And for the next
book I'm working on,

00:34:24.170 --> 00:34:25.679
it's the same thing.

00:34:25.679 --> 00:34:28.550
I'm trying to just make sure
that I'm immersed enough

00:34:28.550 --> 00:34:33.030
that I can cherry pick a
few fun details off the top.

00:34:33.030 --> 00:34:34.517
RICK KLAU: Question right here.

00:34:34.517 --> 00:34:36.600
AUDIENCE: One of the most
interesting things to me

00:34:36.600 --> 00:34:39.024
about your first trilogy,
and-- I haven't read it yet,

00:34:39.024 --> 00:34:41.530
but from what I understand this
book as well is that you've

00:34:41.530 --> 00:34:43.370
got female protagonists.

00:34:43.370 --> 00:34:45.429
And it's relatively
rare for authors

00:34:45.429 --> 00:34:47.489
to cross the gender barrier.

00:34:47.489 --> 00:34:49.770
And it's also relatively
rare in science fiction

00:34:49.770 --> 00:34:51.020
to have female protagonists.

00:34:51.020 --> 00:34:54.260
So can you comment
a little bit on what

00:34:54.260 --> 00:34:55.760
your thought process
going into that

00:34:55.760 --> 00:34:58.652
is, how you channel
the female voice?

00:34:58.652 --> 00:35:00.110
DAVID ALLISON: Four
times in a row.

00:35:02.930 --> 00:35:04.930
ELIOT PEPER: I think I'll
probably keep doing it

00:35:04.930 --> 00:35:07.030
until I stop getting
asked that question.

00:35:07.030 --> 00:35:12.760
Because I think it's sort of
interesting that we have--

00:35:12.760 --> 00:35:16.050
not only that there's
a gender divide

00:35:16.050 --> 00:35:19.950
in terms of creators and
their fictional characters.

00:35:19.950 --> 00:35:23.140
And there are certainly
a lot more female authors

00:35:23.140 --> 00:35:25.540
who write male characters
or protagonists

00:35:25.540 --> 00:35:28.420
than there are male authors
who write female protagonists.

00:35:28.420 --> 00:35:30.760
But honestly, I
think there's sort

00:35:30.760 --> 00:35:36.550
of a dearth of female
protagonists in general,

00:35:36.550 --> 00:35:38.865
basically in pretty
much every format.

00:35:41.560 --> 00:35:45.150
So I guess to a
certain extent, that's

00:35:45.150 --> 00:35:47.260
certainly how I think about it.

00:35:47.260 --> 00:35:51.520
But it's sort of
funny, because I don't

00:35:51.520 --> 00:35:54.970
do much to channel any voice.

00:35:54.970 --> 00:35:58.730
And I think that may be
doing a disservice to,

00:35:58.730 --> 00:36:00.380
I don't know, to someone.

00:36:00.380 --> 00:36:04.570
But I just try to write all
my characters as people,

00:36:04.570 --> 00:36:08.660
and I don't really
think about their gender

00:36:08.660 --> 00:36:10.580
or racial background
or anything else.

00:36:10.580 --> 00:36:13.380
And I think, to a certain
extent, that may actually not

00:36:13.380 --> 00:36:17.750
be super helpful, because
it's hard to-- obviously,

00:36:17.750 --> 00:36:20.350
our circumstances influence
how we experience the world

00:36:20.350 --> 00:36:22.860
and how other people react
to us and stuff like that.

00:36:22.860 --> 00:36:24.470
But when I'm
writing a story, I'm

00:36:24.470 --> 00:36:27.950
really just sort of thinking
about, OK, I'm basically

00:36:27.950 --> 00:36:30.650
imagining myself in your shoes.

00:36:30.650 --> 00:36:33.420
So that's how I approach it.

00:36:33.420 --> 00:36:36.496
And I'm very happy to have a
bunch of female protagonists.

00:36:36.496 --> 00:36:37.870
But really, it
was like, what are

00:36:37.870 --> 00:36:39.990
the characters I'm excited
to write about, and thinking

00:36:39.990 --> 00:36:41.698
about their history
and their background.

00:36:41.698 --> 00:36:43.940
And it came more out
of that than out--

00:36:43.940 --> 00:36:46.510
I wish I could say I
had a big point to make

00:36:46.510 --> 00:36:50.740
and that I was trying to advance
a social goal by doing so.

00:36:50.740 --> 00:36:52.380
But really, it's
because it's fun

00:36:52.380 --> 00:36:55.060
and because I really got into
thinking about those characters

00:36:55.060 --> 00:37:00.090
and imagining who they were as
people and where that would go.

00:37:00.090 --> 00:37:03.750
RICK KLAU: So the week
that "Cumulus" came out

00:37:03.750 --> 00:37:06.202
you got a phone call
from William Gibson?

00:37:06.202 --> 00:37:07.660
ELIOT PEPER: Yeah.

00:37:07.660 --> 00:37:09.470
RICK KLAU: Tell me about that.

00:37:09.470 --> 00:37:13.310
So you hear from the guy who
coined the term "cyberspace"

00:37:13.310 --> 00:37:15.290
and he sort of invented
this whole category

00:37:15.290 --> 00:37:16.830
of science fiction.

00:37:16.830 --> 00:37:17.995
What did you talk about?

00:37:17.995 --> 00:37:23.740
ELIOT PEPER: Yeah, it
was super weird, for me.

00:37:23.740 --> 00:37:27.850
I was like in a fan boy coma.

00:37:27.850 --> 00:37:31.614
So how many of you guys
have read William Gibson,

00:37:31.614 --> 00:37:32.280
just so we know?

00:37:32.280 --> 00:37:33.570
OK, so decent amount.

00:37:33.570 --> 00:37:36.980
So for anybody who hasn't, he's
a very, very well known science

00:37:36.980 --> 00:37:37.630
fiction author.

00:37:37.630 --> 00:37:41.520
And he invented cyberpunk,
which is the genre

00:37:41.520 --> 00:37:42.550
that this book sits in.

00:37:42.550 --> 00:37:47.170
So like that was
really-- it blew my mind.

00:37:47.170 --> 00:37:49.390
So what ended up
happening was "Cumulus"

00:37:49.390 --> 00:37:52.720
came out on a Thursday.

00:37:52.720 --> 00:37:54.870
Website called Ars
Technica reviewed it.

00:37:54.870 --> 00:38:00.590
And someone posted
that review on Reddit.

00:38:00.590 --> 00:38:03.310
And I'm not a very
heavy Reddit user.

00:38:03.310 --> 00:38:06.850
But it went viral.

00:38:06.850 --> 00:38:11.500
It had, like, 2000 up
votes on the first day.

00:38:11.500 --> 00:38:14.530
I'm now learning more
Reddit vocabulary,

00:38:14.530 --> 00:38:16.680
so it was like on front page.

00:38:16.680 --> 00:38:18.280
So that was a big deal.

00:38:18.280 --> 00:38:21.060
But for me experiencing
it, it was very odd,

00:38:21.060 --> 00:38:24.770
because I started getting
texts from friends

00:38:24.770 --> 00:38:27.851
that were screenshots of their
front page with my book on it.

00:38:27.851 --> 00:38:28.850
They're like, oh my God.

00:38:28.850 --> 00:38:30.114
I'm like, what does that mean?

00:38:33.710 --> 00:38:34.560
So that was weird.

00:38:34.560 --> 00:38:37.600
And I was eating breakfast and
I started getting emails just

00:38:37.600 --> 00:38:40.450
to my personal email account.

00:38:40.450 --> 00:38:45.230
I think the first day there
were between half a dozen

00:38:45.230 --> 00:38:49.600
and a dozen inquiries about
film TV rights for the book

00:38:49.600 --> 00:38:53.550
and all of this other
stuff, which blew me away.

00:38:53.550 --> 00:38:57.530
I had basically been sort
of obnoxious and loud

00:38:57.530 --> 00:38:59.570
on social media,
because you do that when

00:38:59.570 --> 00:39:02.550
you're trying to release
something for your first day.

00:39:02.550 --> 00:39:08.150
And I had sent out an email
to my fan reader list.

00:39:08.150 --> 00:39:13.680
And so that's not the
biggest PR strategy.

00:39:13.680 --> 00:39:15.490
I'm an independent author.

00:39:15.490 --> 00:39:16.739
I don't have a PR firm.

00:39:16.739 --> 00:39:17.780
I don't have any of that.

00:39:17.780 --> 00:39:19.510
So it's all been grassroots.

00:39:19.510 --> 00:39:21.880
So this was very weird
and not something I

00:39:21.880 --> 00:39:22.870
was very accustomed to.

00:39:22.870 --> 00:39:25.890
But it was a lot of fun.

00:39:25.890 --> 00:39:30.440
So two days later, I got a
phone call from William Gibson.

00:39:30.440 --> 00:39:33.990
And we basically spent an
hour talking about the book.

00:39:33.990 --> 00:39:37.890
And really, he was giving
me writing advice, which

00:39:37.890 --> 00:39:39.890
I can now pass along to you.

00:39:42.570 --> 00:39:45.400
So he's a super
sweet guy, obviously

00:39:45.400 --> 00:39:47.930
unbelievably brilliant if you've
ever read any of his work.

00:39:47.930 --> 00:39:54.440
But his big tips for new
writers were, one, never

00:39:54.440 --> 00:39:57.555
do a multi-book deal.

00:39:57.555 --> 00:39:59.930
So this means when you're
negotiating with the publisher,

00:39:59.930 --> 00:40:02.860
so if you're selling your book
to a publisher, many of them

00:40:02.860 --> 00:40:05.680
want you to want to
sell them a series.

00:40:05.680 --> 00:40:08.840
So they'll say, we're going
to give you a seven book deal.

00:40:08.840 --> 00:40:10.780
We'll pay you one
advance, seven books,

00:40:10.780 --> 00:40:14.140
and then we'll do some fun
calculus on the back end

00:40:14.140 --> 00:40:18.140
to make sure that we keep
as much of it as we can.

00:40:18.140 --> 00:40:20.320
As they should--
they're a business.

00:40:20.320 --> 00:40:23.410
But his suggestion was,
you never want to do that,

00:40:23.410 --> 00:40:26.890
because if your book does well,
you want to have the leverage

00:40:26.890 --> 00:40:28.120
to get a better second deal.

00:40:28.120 --> 00:40:29.470
I was like, OK, that's good.

00:40:29.470 --> 00:40:30.845
And then a second
piece of advice

00:40:30.845 --> 00:40:34.435
was, don't buy the big house.

00:40:34.435 --> 00:40:36.310
Which go really well
together, because if you

00:40:36.310 --> 00:40:37.980
did a multi-book
deal and then you

00:40:37.980 --> 00:40:41.320
buy the big house and the
deal doesn't work out,

00:40:41.320 --> 00:40:43.940
you've got problems.

00:40:43.940 --> 00:40:45.570
So those were really good.

00:40:45.570 --> 00:40:51.410
And then his third piece of
advice was, keep writing.

00:40:51.410 --> 00:40:57.440
He said that one of the things
he's seen among his friends

00:40:57.440 --> 00:41:00.370
is that those that
were successful writers

00:41:00.370 --> 00:41:04.890
over the long term
actually kept writing.

00:41:04.890 --> 00:41:11.950
So there are probably other
worlds where this happens.

00:41:11.950 --> 00:41:14.220
But in the writing
world, a lot of people

00:41:14.220 --> 00:41:17.660
have dreamed of writing a book.

00:41:17.660 --> 00:41:19.470
I feel like most
people have at least

00:41:19.470 --> 00:41:20.920
thought about it once or twice.

00:41:24.730 --> 00:41:28.070
And so maybe you get
started and you try one.

00:41:28.070 --> 00:41:30.630
But once you've written
a book, many people

00:41:30.630 --> 00:41:31.930
basically stop there.

00:41:31.930 --> 00:41:33.870
So they're happy that
they wrote a book,

00:41:33.870 --> 00:41:37.820
and now they can call
themselves an author, which

00:41:37.820 --> 00:41:40.200
is totally objectively true.

00:41:40.200 --> 00:41:43.800
But if you're trying
to both be an author

00:41:43.800 --> 00:41:47.260
and be a commercially
successful author,

00:41:47.260 --> 00:41:48.990
those are very different things.

00:41:48.990 --> 00:41:52.030
And if you want the latter,
you need to do a lot of it.

00:41:57.200 --> 00:42:02.480
I try to think of it as a
verb rather than as a noun.

00:42:02.480 --> 00:42:04.470
And that also means
it's very democratic.

00:42:04.470 --> 00:42:07.890
If you want to be a
writer, start writing,

00:42:07.890 --> 00:42:09.872
and you've already
achieved your goal.

00:42:09.872 --> 00:42:12.080
I think that's actually one
of the really cool pieces

00:42:12.080 --> 00:42:12.830
about it.

00:42:12.830 --> 00:42:15.500
Most of us have
learned to write.

00:42:15.500 --> 00:42:18.100
But on the back end,
you need to keep writing

00:42:18.100 --> 00:42:19.790
if you want to stay a writer.

00:42:19.790 --> 00:42:24.190
And you don't want to get
distracted by, I don't know.

00:42:24.190 --> 00:42:25.860
Like, say maybe you
came out with a book

00:42:25.860 --> 00:42:27.160
and it's very successful.

00:42:27.160 --> 00:42:30.710
Maybe you're distracted by
celebrity or other things

00:42:30.710 --> 00:42:32.310
that the book brings
into your life.

00:42:32.310 --> 00:42:34.120
And what ends up
happening is sometimes

00:42:34.120 --> 00:42:35.870
people write one really
good book and then

00:42:35.870 --> 00:42:38.090
they forget to keep writing.

00:42:38.090 --> 00:42:41.380
And so that was his other
piece of advice, which

00:42:41.380 --> 00:42:43.736
I am trying to take to heart.

00:42:43.736 --> 00:42:45.944
RICK KLAU: With that, I
think we're out of time.

00:42:45.944 --> 00:42:47.810
Eliot, thanks very
much for coming out.

00:42:47.810 --> 00:42:49.320
ELIOT PEPER: Thanks
for having me.

00:42:49.320 --> 00:42:53.570
[APPLAUSE]

